We recommended that Management:
Direct the GSO Designate, in coordination with the Appraisal and Disposal Committee, to finalize the IIRUP by providing a reasonable appraisal value for the unserviceable properties and to promptly cause the disposal of these properties;
Direct the GSO to include in the IIRUP all items not only equipment and machines but also buildings, infrastructure assets, and other structures which are determined to be unserviceable;
Advise the concerned personnel to submit the IIRUP to the accounting office upon completion of the disposal activity as it will be the basis for adjusting the balances of the affected PPE accounts; and
Direct the accounting office to cease the recording of Depreciation Expense for the demolished building.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the IC to conduct complete physical count of all inventories in accordance with the prescribed rules;
Require the MAO to maintain SLCs. Likewise, we also recommend that the GSO maintain a complete and appropriate SCs for each type of supplies and materials;
Conduct regular reconciliation of the SLCs and SCs to ensure that all purchases and issuances are properly accounted for; and
Require the MA to record inventory using the prescribed perpetual method to ensure reliability and accuracy of the accounts presented in the FS.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Prioritize filling vacant plantilla positions and, when necessary, utilize casual or emergency staff hiring practices in accordance with CSC guidelines and other relevant rule and regulations;
Undertake a comprehensive study and analysis of the Municipality’s staffing pattern to develop a reliable HRP. Furthermore, we recommend the implementation of EO No. 36 of 2024, or an internal policy for establishing internal policy for hiring JO/COS in the Municipality to provide clear guidelines and controls over the hiring of JO/COS personnel;
Consider incorporating the expertise of the MHRO by formally integrating them into the hiring process for JO/COS personnel;
Direct the MHRMO to review and assess existing JO/COS agreements, specifically focusing on defining the required hours for assigned tasks and duties to ensure fair compensation, efficient resource allocation, adherence to contractual obligations, and the effective delivery of services by the Municipality;
Direct the MHRO, with the assistance of the Municipal Accounting Office, to investigate instances where JO personnel have declared performing duties different from those originally assigned and stipulated in their contracts. This investigation should aim to determine the reasons for these discrepancies and ensure adherence to the provisions stipulated in their contracts; and
Consider implementing a separate attendance monitoring system specifically designed for JO personnel performing tasks outside the physical confines of the Municipal Building. This measure would enhance the accuracy and verifiability of their time records and help prevent potential inaccuracies or misuse of resources.
We also recommended and Management agreed to furnish the Office of the Auditor with copy of perfected JO/COS contracts.

We recommended that the LCE:
Direct the Property Officer to conduct physical count of all inventory items every semester and prepare the RPCI within the prescribed period as prescribed by the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs.  Thereafter, require the Property Officer and the MA to reconcile the RPCI and the accounting records of any variance;
Require the Property Officer and the MA to maintain complete and updated SCs and SLCs, respectively, and reconcile their records regularly.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the MA to verify meticulously the status of long outstanding FTs still maintained in the books and adhere strictly to the provisions of Section 111 of P.D. 1445;
Require the MA to prepare liquidation reports of outstanding FTs, the purposes of which are already completed and submit thereof, including the return of any unspent amount of the FTs to the concerned SAs in accordance with Section 4 of COA Circular No. 94-013. Accordingly, record in the books of accounts the liquidation/settlement of these FTs as deduction to the Due to NGAs account;
Direct the OIC-MT to facilitate the transfer of the total balance of cash awards amounting to ₱129,356.15from the TF books to the GF books while the MA prepare the necessary Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to adjust the cash prizes received, recorded under the Due to NGAs account in the TF books, as a prior period adjustment credited to equity as income in the GF books.  The amount shall be available for appropriation maybe for health related projects since the cash awards were received from DOH on account for excellence in implementation of health programs;
Require the MA to confirm the FTs to the SAs to verify the existence of liabilities and correctness of the balances;
In cases where the disposition of unspent or unutilized amounts is not provided for in the MOA, Trust Agreement, or Memorandum of Understanding, Management may opt to seek approval from the SAs to utilize the remaining unexpended balances of the FTs;
Direct the responsible Departments to expedite the implementation of FTs, since the necessary resources are readily available. This will ensure that the MGG can pursue the targeted PPAs without delay or disruption; and
Instruct the MA and the MEO to formally direct the Contractor of the finished RHU Rehabilitation project to facilitate the submission of necessary documents so that payment of the accomplished work and proper accounting thereof can be done soonest.

We recommended that the LCE:

Instruct the MA to account properly for the acquisition and issuance of Construction Materials inventory based on IPSAS 12, and make the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balances of the affected inventory and CIP accounts;

Require the MT and/or Supply Officer and the MA to maintain properly and update the stock cards and SLCs, respectively, and reconcile their records regularly;

Require the MHRMO to issue uniform policy guidelines on hiring of JO personnel to strengthen internal controls pertaining thereto;

Facilitate the immediate completion of delayed infrastructure projects through constant monitoring and coordination with concerned personnel/departments;

Ensure that all disbursements are supported with proper documentation prior to payment to avoid future suspension or disallowance in audit; and

Comply strictly with GPPB Resolution No. 20-2020 and OSHS in the implementation of infrastructure projects by administration.

We recommended that the LCE:

Increase the bonding requirements of the DO pursuant to Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 to protect the interest of the MGG, otherwise ensure that CAs granted is within the limit of her fidelity bond;

Require the concerned DO to settle immediately her outstanding CAs due for liquidation by demanding the submission of liquidation reports and supporting documents. Otherwise, cause the withholding or suspension of her salaries for non-compliance therewith;

Strengthen control measures to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and full accounting of balances of CAs by monitoring strictly the period of liquidation and impose sanctions on AO who failed to liquidate on time; and

Comply strictly with the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended that the LCE:

Expedite the revision of its 10-year Municipal SWM Plan and submit the same to the DENR-EMB for approval of the NSWMC;

Comply strictly with the requirements of RA No. 9003 particularly on the efficient collection, proper transfer and transport of wastes; efficient management of residuals; adoption of modern technologies for destruction/reuse of residuals wastes; and competent operation of final disposal sites;

Request the assistance of the DENR to conduct site assessment on the TRCA to evaluate whether the site conditions are compliant with the parameters provided under the NSWMC Resolution No. 64, series of 2013;

Prioritize provision/allocation of enough budget for full implementation of SWM programs and projects to address all identified key issues as provided in the Municipal SWM plan; and

Encourage the barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes.

We recommended that the LCE:

Ensure that Municipal GFPS is fully functional and members are capable to promote gender mainstreaming pursuant to PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;

Direct the GAD Focal Person to facilitate the preparation and submission of GPB and GAD AR;

Establish immediately GAD database that will serve as basis for gender responsive planning, programming and policy formulations;

Formulate policies on gender mainstreaming such as the local GAD code or ordinances that will support the Municipality’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling women’s human rights towards gender-equality and women empowerment; and

Send competent staff/member of the GFPS to trainings on how to use monitoring tools such as the HGDG and PIMME in monitoring and evaluation of results of GAD PPAs that would aid in assessing the effectiveness and efficiency of the LGU’s gender mainstreaming efforts.

