We recommended that the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board:

Exert effort to expedite the approval of the 10-year SWM Plan 2016-2026; 

Involve closely the Barangay officials in the strict implementation of the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign on the “no segregation, no collection policy and the “no-littering policy” among the residents;

Exercise strong political will to implement the environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment as mandated under RA No. 9003; and

Implement the garbage collection fee as provided in Section 1, Article N of the 2005 Revenue Code of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor/Treasurer strategize how to efficiently and effectively collect taxes and consider, among others, the following measures:

Conduct information and education campaign/activities, e.g. social media/radio, and other means of communication to encourage land owners to pay regularly their tax obligation and the benefits of paying early and/or on time. Consider condonation of fines and penalties to delinquent tax payers;

Issue letters of demand to delinquent taxpayers with information on the possible consequences for non-payment of taxes; 

Develop collection strategies to enhance collection of taxes like seeking the assistance of barangay officials in the house-to house campaign; 

Post the notice of delinquency in the payment of real property tax in the main entrance of the municipal building and other conspicuous public places frequently visited by people; 

Prepare the list of all delinquent real property taxes and submit the same to the SB with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection of those taxes; and

Avail of the remedies by administrative action thru levy on real property or by judicial action.

We recommended and the LCE:

Consider initiating the development or acquisition of a computerized payroll system for a more accurate and efficient processing of the employees’ payroll and related accounts; 

Direct the Human Resource Department Head to improve the efficiency and data capture in payroll preparation so that all employees are captured in the remittance list once their contributions and amortizations are deducted from their gross earnings; 

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to 

continue being compliant in the deduction and remittance of premium contributions and loan amortizations to the GSIS/PhilHealth/Pag-IBIG;

perform a reconciliation of the amounts withheld or deducted with the amounts remitted to determine the actual amounts due to GSIS/PhilHealth/Pag-IBIG and prepare a necessary adjusting entry if any.

We recommended that Management:

Demand from the Municipal Treasurer and other concerned officials and employees the immediate liquidation of their outstanding cash advances specifically those granted in previous years. Otherwise, withhold any money due them until such time that their cash advances are settled;

Immediately stop the grant of additional cash advances to all officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances until such time that previous cash advances are fully settled. Issuance of the required certification from the Municipal Accountant that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books under COA Circular No. 2012-001 should be strictly complied with; 

Take appropriate legal actions against those erring accountable officers/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted; and

Institute measures to avoid the accumulation of cash advances related to special purpose/time-bound undertakings such as, but not limited to, proper planning of activities to facilitate the direct payment to providers of goods and services and designation of special disbursing officer/s to those directly involved in any undertaking to make them primarily accountable on the cash advances made.

